SIMPLE: tweedle
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tweedle
<hw>Twee"dle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf.
<er>Twiddle</er>.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>twidle</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To handle lightly; -- said
with reference to awkward fiddling; hence, to influence as if by
fiddling; to coax; to allure.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A fiddler brought in with him a body of lusty young fellows, whom
he had <qex>tweedled</qex> into the service.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To twist.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tweedledum and Tweedledee</ent>⟦br⟧
